                                <p> By Isabel Reynolds</p>
                                <p> TOKYO, Sept 23 (Reuters) - Japan's faltering main  opposition party voted for more of the same on Monday,  re-electing a leader criticised by many for failing to provide  a convincing alternative to Prime Minister Junichiro Koizumi.</p>
                                <p> Political blueblood Yukio Hatoyama scraped back as leader  of the Democratic Party of Japan (DPJ) after a close run-off  with arch-rival Naoto Kan.</p>
                                <p> "The result was almost a dead heat with Mr Kan. That means  you are telling me I must not simply carry on as before. I must  become a new Hatoyama," a solemn Hatoyama told party members  after hearing the results of the election at a Tokyo hotel.</p>
                                <p> A fourth generation politician from a wealthy family, the  55-year-old Hatoyama has yet to live up to a pedigree that  includes a prime minister grandfather.</p>
                                <p> Despite repeated pledges to oust the long-ruling Liberal  Democratic Party to which he once belonged, Hatoyama -- once  dubbed "soft cream" for his wishy-washy image -- presides over  a party bereft of a distinctive agenda after Koizumi swept to  power on a reform ticket last year.</p>
                                <p> With Koizumi riding high in the polls following his  historic summit with North Korean leader Kim Jong-Il, public  support for the Democrats fell to eight percent in a Kyodo news  agency poll last week.</p>
                                <p> Critics say Hatoyama lacks the punch to stand up to ruling  party politicians in parliamentary debates and his policies  amount to little more than sniping at government decisions.</p>
                                <p> KAN COULDN'T</p>
                                <p> An engineering graduate of Japan's elite Tokyo University  and holder of a Stanford University doctorate, Hatoyama had  threatened to quit politics if he lost the leadership election.</p>
                                <p> The election result was a disappointment for his more  charismatic rival, former party leader Naoto Kan, once the most  popular politician in Japan.</p>
                                <p> Kan's support among the general public soared when he  fought for an investigation into a government cover-up of  HIV-tainted blood imports in 1996. He was once regularly voted  the man most people wanted to see as prime minister.</p>
                                <p> But Kan fell from grace after reports of an extra-marital  affair, losing the party leadership to Hatoyama in 1999.</p>
                                <p> "I would like to work with Mr Hatoyama's Democratic Party  for a change in government," Kan said after the result was  announced.</p>
                                <p> With only around a quarter of the seats in parliament's  lower house, the Democrats are a long way from being able to  realise Kan's dream.</p>
                                <p> The Democrats also suffer from their image as an uneasy  amalgam of former Socialists, one-time LDP members and a hefty  sprinkling of younger lawmakers.    </p>
